### _Hooke's Law_

When we try to extend a spring by pulling it apart or compressing it with both hands, each of our hands will be subjected to an opposing force by the spring. We refer to this force as the tension or compression in the spring. For our purposes, we usually consider light springs of negligible mass. In 1676, Robert Hooke stated an empirical law that allows us to calculate the magnitude of this force.

Hooke's Law states that the **magnitude of force _F_**exerted by a spring* on a body attached to the spring is proportional to the **extension**\(x\) of the spring from its natural length provided the proportional limit of the spring is not exceeded.

\[F=k\mathbf{x}\]

\(k=\) constant of proportionality (also referred to as force constant or spring constant or stiffness of spring)

