### Couple

**Definition of a Couple**

A pair of forces, which are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction, whose lines of action do not coincide.

Couples produce **only rotation** but no translation.

An example of a couple is shown in the figure below.

Taking moments about the centre of mass, the torque due to the couple \(=\)\(\left(\frac{1}{2}x\right)F+\left(\frac{1}{2}x\right)\)\(=\)\(xF\) (in the clockwise direction),

where \(F\) is the magnitude of the forces and \(x\) is the _perpendicular distance_ between the lines of action.

In fact, taking moments about **any point** would produce the same result.

**Torque of a couple** is the product of the perpendicular distance between the lines of action of the forces and the magnitude of one of the forces.

